1
00:00:00,769 --> 00:00:02,080
Welcome to Creation Talk.

2
00:00:02,104 --> 00:00:04,215
Today we’ll be
answering the question

3
00:00:04,239 --> 00:00:07,928
“How did saltwater and
freshwater fish survive the Flood?”

4
00:00:16,354 --> 00:00:17,738
Welcome to Creation Talk.

5
00:00:17,762 --> 00:00:20,275
My name is Joel Tay,
and this is Dr Robert Carter.

6
00:00:20,299 --> 00:00:21,220
Hey Joel.

7
00:00:21,244 --> 00:00:22,091
Hi.

8
00:00:22,115 --> 00:00:24,813
Today we are dealing
with this question.

9
00:00:24,837 --> 00:00:26,011
Sometimes we are asked,

10
00:00:26,035 --> 00:00:30,407
“How did freshwater and
saltwater fish survive the Flood?”

11
00:00:30,709 --> 00:00:33,736
Why do people even
ask this question?

12
00:00:33,760 --> 00:00:37,826
Well, most people know that
freshwater fish don’t survive in salt water.

13
00:00:37,850 --> 00:00:39,191
And when you read Scripture

14
00:00:39,215 --> 00:00:41,834
—in fact I’ve got it right here,
ready to go—

15
00:00:41,858 --> 00:00:45,247
Genesis chapter 7 verse 19,

16
00:00:45,271 --> 00:00:47,867
“And the waters prevailed
so mightily on the earth that

17
00:00:47,891 --> 00:00:51,041
all the high mountains under
the whole heaven were covered.”

18
00:00:51,065 --> 00:00:52,311
And this is the Flood?

19
00:00:52,335 --> 00:00:53,485
This is during the Flood.

20
00:00:53,509 --> 00:00:54,509
And what it means is that

21
00:00:54,533 --> 00:00:59,252
the oceans overwhelmed all
the freshwater places on land,

22
00:00:59,276 --> 00:01:00,598
setting up a massive problem:

23
00:01:00,622 --> 00:01:05,139
Doesn’t that mean all the
freshwater fish would go extinct
if it really was a global Flood?

24
00:01:05,163 --> 00:01:09,892
So how does a fish survive
in salt water or fresh water?

25
00:01:09,916 --> 00:01:13,138
Is it just a biology question?

26
00:01:13,162 --> 00:01:15,067
It’s partially a biology question.

27
00:01:15,091 --> 00:01:17,095
It’s partially a time question.

28
00:01:17,119 --> 00:01:19,480
But the biology is
actually really interesting.

29
00:01:19,504 --> 00:01:22,033
Most fish are what
are called ‘stenohaline’.

30
00:01:22,057 --> 00:01:23,248
What’s that?

31
00:01:23,272 --> 00:01:26,489
That means they can only
survive in fresh water or salt water.

32
00:01:26,513 --> 00:01:27,702
That is true today.

33
00:01:27,726 --> 00:01:28,543
Okay.

34
00:01:28,567 --> 00:01:31,749
But a lot of fish are
called ‘euryhaline’.

35
00:01:31,773 --> 00:01:33,431
They can go either way.

36
00:01:33,455 --> 00:01:34,948
The famous one is salmon.

37
00:01:34,972 --> 00:01:35,702
Salmon? Yes.

38
00:01:35,726 --> 00:01:37,104
They’re called ‘anadromous’.

39
00:01:37,128 --> 00:01:39,817
They spend most
their time in salt water

40
00:01:39,841 --> 00:01:42,283
but they go into
fresh water to spawn.

41
00:01:42,307 --> 00:01:45,688
But sturgeon, smelt,

42
00:01:45,712 --> 00:01:48,872
some stingrays,
famously the bull shark,

43
00:01:48,896 --> 00:01:51,016
bullshark can swim hundreds
of miles up the Mississippi,

44
00:01:51,040 --> 00:01:53,425
hundreds of miles up the Amazon,

45
00:01:53,449 --> 00:01:56,648
So you can actually get a
shark attack in fresh water.

46
00:01:56,672 --> 00:01:57,331
Yeah!

47
00:01:57,355 --> 00:01:59,347
And so …
There’s a lot of species that do that.

48
00:01:59,371 --> 00:02:03,177
But then, on the other way there’s
some fish that are called ‘catadromous’.

49
00:02:03,201 --> 00:02:03,863
Yes.

50
00:02:03,887 --> 00:02:07,100
They spend most of the time in fresh water
and then they come into salt water to spawn.

51
00:02:07,124 --> 00:02:09,949
like the North American
and the European eel—

52
00:02:09,973 --> 00:02:11,154
famous for for doing that.

53
00:02:11,178 --> 00:02:13,662
And there’s another fish
called the barramundi, from Asia.

54
00:02:13,686 --> 00:02:16,132
And there are actually some
populations of barramundi now

55
00:02:16,156 --> 00:02:18,116
that never go back
into fresh water.

56
00:02:18,140 --> 00:02:21,527
So they have adapted, they have changed,
into a new environment?

57
00:02:21,551 --> 00:02:22,522
Is that what you’re saying?

58
00:02:22,546 --> 00:02:23,436
Yeah.

59
00:02:23,460 --> 00:02:26,823
But, fish do struggle with salt.

60
00:02:26,847 --> 00:02:34,301
I mean a saltwater fish is constantly
drinking and constantly excreting salt.

61
00:02:34,325 --> 00:02:37,085
If they don’t do that the salt in
the water will overwhelm them.

62
00:02:37,109 --> 00:02:39,706
There’s a lot less salt in
fish meat than in the water.

63
00:02:39,730 --> 00:02:40,731
Okay.

64
00:02:40,755 --> 00:02:42,628
The opposite is
true in fresh water.

65
00:02:42,652 --> 00:02:45,213
A freshwater fish has
to constantly urinate.

66
00:02:45,237 --> 00:02:48,355
He’s absorbing water through
his gills and he’s got to get rid of it

67
00:02:48,379 --> 00:02:52,468
because there’s a lot less salt in
fresh water than there is in fish meat.

68
00:02:52,492 --> 00:02:55,936
So this is two completely
different biological processes?

69
00:02:55,960 --> 00:03:00,139
Yeah. They’re struggling in
different ways with salt concentration.

70
00:03:00,163 --> 00:03:03,857
But some fish can
swim from salt water,

71
00:03:03,881 --> 00:03:06,227
they take a day or two to adjust,
now they’re in fresh water

72
00:03:06,251 --> 00:03:07,389
and vice versa.

73
00:03:07,413 --> 00:03:08,878
So Rob didn’t you tell me a story

74
00:03:08,902 --> 00:03:12,939
about you trying to grow
freshwater fish in a saltwater tank

75
00:03:12,963 --> 00:03:14,181
or something like that?

76
00:03:14,205 --> 00:03:15,714
Actually what I said was,

77
00:03:15,738 --> 00:03:18,023
during my years of marine biology

78
00:03:18,047 --> 00:03:20,329
when I had to start
a saltwater tank

79
00:03:20,353 --> 00:03:21,377
um,

80
00:03:21,401 --> 00:03:22,997
a lot of times when
you start a tank

81
00:03:23,021 --> 00:03:26,069
there’s a lot of chemical
changes and fish tend to die

82
00:03:26,093 --> 00:03:29,920
and so you don’t want to put an expensive
saltwater fish in your brand new tank.

83
00:03:29,944 --> 00:03:32,529
What you do is you go to the aquarium
store and get a freshwater molly,

84
00:03:32,553 --> 00:03:33,680
for a dollar

85
00:03:33,704 --> 00:03:34,313
Uh-hm.

86
00:03:34,337 --> 00:03:36,056
and use that fish
to start off your tank

87
00:03:36,080 --> 00:03:38,284
because a molly works
great in salt water.

88
00:03:38,308 --> 00:03:41,165
Now you don’t want to just throw
him in the salt water, he’d probably die.

89
00:03:41,189 --> 00:03:46,669
So if you slowly add salt water
to the container the fish is in
over a couple of hours,

90
00:03:46,693 --> 00:03:50,197
you just release him and he’ll be just
fine in salt water for the rest of his life.

91
00:03:50,221 --> 00:03:52,575
So how does that
fish help the tank?

92
00:03:52,599 --> 00:03:58,005
By eating and by excreting he’s
producing nutrients for the bacteria.

93
00:03:58,029 --> 00:03:59,536
So beneficial bacteria,
that sort of thing?

94
00:03:59,560 --> 00:04:02,603
Yeah, so you can start building
up a bacterial population in the tank.

95
00:04:02,627 --> 00:04:07,835
If you just throw a whole bunch of
fish into a fish tank without bacteria
ready they’ll pollute themselves.

96
00:04:07,860 --> 00:04:10,091
So what you did is you
slowly changed the water

97
00:04:10,115 --> 00:04:13,228
and let it adapt from
fresh water to salt water?

98
00:04:13,252 --> 00:04:13,916
Yeah.

99
00:04:13,940 --> 00:04:16,616
And then you finally add
in with a saltwater fish.

100
00:04:16,640 --> 00:04:18,109
Yeah then just put
them in the fish tank.

101
00:04:18,133 --> 00:04:19,502
Pure salt water.

102
00:04:19,526 --> 00:04:21,042
They’ll do just fine.

103
00:04:21,066 --> 00:04:23,855
So for the fish that can
only survive in fresh water

104
00:04:23,879 --> 00:04:25,863
or only survive in salt water,

105
00:04:25,887 --> 00:04:29,577
how do we explain that if the Flood
is only a few thousand years ago?

106
00:04:29,601 --> 00:04:32,426
How … Why are they like that now?

107
00:04:32,450 --> 00:04:35,578
There’s actually a lot … there’s several
different important things to consider.

108
00:04:35,602 --> 00:04:36,389
When we’re just …

109
00:04:36,413 --> 00:04:38,293
Talking about fresh water—
that’s really the problem.

110
00:04:38,317 --> 00:04:41,196
It’s not the saltwater fish, it’s the
freshwater fish that are the problem.

111
00:04:41,220 --> 00:04:42,217
Why is that?

112
00:04:42,241 --> 00:04:43,594
Because the oceans are salty

113
00:04:43,618 --> 00:04:48,398
and if the oceans come up onto land
then it’s not a problem with the
saltwater fish, during the Flood.

114
00:04:48,422 --> 00:04:52,719
It’s the freshwater fish that
live on land during the Flood
that we have a problem with.

115
00:04:52,743 --> 00:04:56,130
So how do we get
freshwater fish today?

116
00:04:56,154 --> 00:04:58,520
I mean fish that only
survive in fresh water.

117
00:04:58,544 --> 00:05:00,202
There’s several different ways.

118
00:05:00,226 --> 00:05:01,451
First of all,

119
00:05:01,475 --> 00:05:05,134
just because a fish species
today can’t tolerate salt water

120
00:05:05,158 --> 00:05:08,595
doesn’t mean its ancestors
couldn’t tolerate salt water.

121
00:05:08,619 --> 00:05:11,388
So you’re saying that they
used to be able to tolerate both

122
00:05:11,412 --> 00:05:13,578
and they kind of lose one ability?

123
00:05:13,602 --> 00:05:14,762
Quite possibly.

124
00:05:14,786 --> 00:05:19,291
If you have a fish species living way up
in the Amazon and it never sees salt water,

125
00:05:19,315 --> 00:05:21,518
well if there’s a gene that
helps to tolerate salt water

126
00:05:21,542 --> 00:05:23,927
and that gene gets deleted
or broken or something

127
00:05:23,951 --> 00:05:26,088
it doesn’t affect the fish.

128
00:05:26,112 --> 00:05:27,533
So you’re telling me that

129
00:05:27,557 --> 00:05:31,018
fish changed very quickly
after the time of the Flood,

130
00:05:31,042 --> 00:05:32,716
a few thousand years ago

131
00:05:32,740 --> 00:05:38,543
and they specialized because
they lost some ability to adapt
to either salt or fresh water.

132
00:05:38,567 --> 00:05:39,656
Is that what you’re saying?

133
00:05:39,680 --> 00:05:41,020
Ah, that’s exactly what I’m saying.

134
00:05:41,044 --> 00:05:44,957
A lot of adaptation that we see
is a loss of ability to do something,

135
00:05:44,981 --> 00:05:48,108
a species getting
fine-tuned to an environment.

136
00:05:48,132 --> 00:05:51,397
But once it becomes
fine-tuned and highly specialized

137
00:05:51,421 --> 00:05:52,933
well it’s not a generalist anymore,
and

138
00:05:52,957 --> 00:05:57,257
it would have actually have a problem
living in some of the environments
that its ancestors could live in.

139
00:05:57,281 --> 00:06:00,290
Okay this is kind of
interesting because I think

140
00:06:00,314 --> 00:06:06,455
a lot of people have this idea that
evolution believes in change and
creation doesn’t believe in change

141
00:06:06,479 --> 00:06:09,412
but you’re telling me that the Word of God,
the Bible, tells us that

142
00:06:09,436 --> 00:06:12,340
creatures would have
to adapt very quickly.

143
00:06:12,364 --> 00:06:13,873
So it’s actually the creation …

144
00:06:13,897 --> 00:06:15,468
—if I’m getting,
if I’m getting this right—

145
00:06:15,492 --> 00:06:19,388
creationists are actually the
ones who believe in rapid changes.

146
00:06:19,412 --> 00:06:19,895
Yes.

147
00:06:19,919 --> 00:06:22,284
And evolutionists are the ones
who believe in slow changes.

148
00:06:22,308 --> 00:06:24,531
Yes. And the reason they
believe in slow changes is because

149
00:06:24,555 --> 00:06:28,974
Charles Darwin told us it takes a long time
and species change over millions of years.

150
00:06:28,999 --> 00:06:32,476
So change over time is
consistent with the Word of God,

151
00:06:32,500 --> 00:06:33,493
rapid changes in fact.

152
00:06:33,517 --> 00:06:37,267
Yeah. The issue is that the
word evolution means change.

153
00:06:37,291 --> 00:06:37,752
Uh-hm.

154
00:06:37,776 --> 00:06:40,332
And so a lot of people, when they
ask them for a definition of evolution

155
00:06:40,356 --> 00:06:42,437
they say “Oh, evolution is
just change over time”.

156
00:06:42,461 --> 00:06:46,102
Yeah, it’s true. I mean all my textbooks,
they define evolution as change over time.

157
00:06:46,126 --> 00:06:48,433
Yeah!
But that’s the lamest possible definition

158
00:06:48,457 --> 00:06:51,371
because I believe in change over
time and I’m not even an evolutionist.

159
00:06:51,395 --> 00:06:54,457
Oh, and like you say,
we believe in rapid change over time.

160
00:06:54,481 --> 00:06:55,176
Yeah!

161
00:06:55,200 --> 00:06:58,961
So just because there’s change
doesn’t mean evolution is true because

162
00:06:58,985 --> 00:07:03,285
evolution is really a belief in
the common ancestry of all things.

163
00:07:03,309 --> 00:07:04,016
Ah!

164
00:07:04,040 --> 00:07:06,127
So really that
definition should be:

165
00:07:06,151 --> 00:07:11,867
‘Enough change over enough time
can theoretically lead to the
common ancestry of all things.’

166
00:07:11,891 --> 00:07:15,735
So why don’t they define
evolution as common ancestry?

167
00:07:15,759 --> 00:07:18,828
I don’t know and it’s frustrating

168
00:07:18,852 --> 00:07:21,115
because what if the
change is downhill?

169
00:07:21,139 --> 00:07:23,265
What if the changes go backwards?

170
00:07:23,289 --> 00:07:27,190
What if we see fish getting bigger and
fish getting smaller over over decades

171
00:07:27,214 --> 00:07:28,652
because of different
environmental pressures?

172
00:07:28,676 --> 00:07:31,629
That’s not any sort of a
common ancestry argument.

173
00:07:31,653 --> 00:07:35,024
That’s just God and his brilliance.

174
00:07:35,048 --> 00:07:39,842
When He created the species,
He created them to be able to adapt.

175
00:07:39,866 --> 00:07:40,484
Okay …

176
00:07:40,508 --> 00:07:46,048
So adaptations and change,
rapid change is an argument for design?

177
00:07:46,072 --> 00:07:51,002
For design! For the smartness of God who put
into his creation the ability to do that.

178
00:07:51,026 --> 00:07:52,868
And even when you
see the fish change

179
00:07:52,892 --> 00:07:56,535
by losing the ability to adapt
to either salt or fresh water

180
00:07:56,559 --> 00:07:58,701
that would be a loss.

181
00:07:58,725 --> 00:07:59,344
Yeah.

182
00:07:59,368 --> 00:08:00,937
So that’s what I mean by downhill.

183
00:08:00,961 --> 00:08:03,264
Yeah. Most of the changes
we see are actually downhill.

184
00:08:03,288 --> 00:08:06,289
They’re … It’s purging away
information that’s not needed,

185
00:08:06,313 --> 00:08:08,196
or something breaking

186
00:08:08,220 --> 00:08:10,372
and that’s the types
of adaptation we see.

187
00:08:10,396 --> 00:08:12,364
We’ve written a lot about that.

188
00:08:12,388 --> 00:08:14,673
There’s tons of
stuff on creation.com

189
00:08:14,697 --> 00:08:17,175
Natural Selection Q&A page,
Speciation Q&A page.

190
00:08:17,199 --> 00:08:20,115
It’s just part of
the creation model.

191
00:08:20,139 --> 00:08:21,654
Oh, that’s wonderful.

192
00:08:21,678 --> 00:08:26,463
So … But does salt water
and fresh water mix together?

193
00:08:26,487 --> 00:08:27,535
Only sort of.

194
00:08:27,559 --> 00:08:31,157
And you’re hinting at something
that I told you earlier today.

195
00:08:31,181 --> 00:08:34,001
When Europeans
discovered the Amazon …

196
00:08:34,025 --> 00:08:34,649
Yes.

197
00:08:34,673 --> 00:08:36,808
they weren’t in sight of land.

198
00:08:36,832 --> 00:08:38,121
They weren’t in sight of land?

199
00:08:38,145 --> 00:08:39,407
They were not in sight of land.

200
00:08:39,431 --> 00:08:40,311
So where were they?

201
00:08:40,335 --> 00:08:43,057
They were way out in the ocean,
in a sailboat

202
00:08:43,081 --> 00:08:46,851
and as they’re sailing across
the ocean they crossed some
water they had a different color

203
00:08:46,875 --> 00:08:49,702
and they said wait a
minute—this is fresh water!

204
00:08:49,726 --> 00:08:53,002
So they turned and sailed right
into the mouth of the Amazon.

205
00:08:53,026 --> 00:08:54,537
They were way over the horizon.

206
00:08:54,561 --> 00:08:56,149
They might have
been 50 miles offshore.

207
00:08:56,173 --> 00:08:57,736
I don’t know how far
offshore they were,

208
00:08:57,760 --> 00:09:00,362
but it was a long way and they just
followed the fresh water into the Amazon.

209
00:09:00,386 --> 00:09:03,386
So there was fresh water more than …
like way out there,

210
00:09:03,410 --> 00:09:05,576
and it did not mix
with the salt water?

211
00:09:05,600 --> 00:09:08,989
That’s right, because fresh
water isn’t as dense as salt water.

212
00:09:09,013 --> 00:09:13,822
Salt makes the salt water heavier and the
fresh water tends to float on salt water.

213
00:09:13,846 --> 00:09:16,422
And sometimes it can
float for a very long time

214
00:09:16,446 --> 00:09:22,866
Okay, so why would this be something
that we would consider when we talk
about the worldwide Flood?

215
00:09:22,890 --> 00:09:27,665
Because the rain that came down during
the Flood would have been fresh water.

216
00:09:27,689 --> 00:09:34,030
And theoretically, possibly we
could get a freshwater lens on top
of the oceans during the Flood

217
00:09:34,054 --> 00:09:37,324
which would provide an
environment for fish to survive

218
00:09:37,348 --> 00:09:41,005
if they were fish that could
not survive in salt water.

219
00:09:41,029 --> 00:09:44,386
And that water would not mix very quickly.
It would take a while for it to …

220
00:09:44,410 --> 00:09:46,147
It depends on the
salinity difference,

221
00:09:46,171 --> 00:09:47,227
it depends on the
temperature difference

222
00:09:47,251 --> 00:09:49,354
it depends on how
much stirring there is.

223
00:09:49,378 --> 00:09:49,901
Oh, that’s interesting.

224
00:09:49,925 --> 00:09:51,081
But it can last for a long time.

225
00:09:51,105 --> 00:09:54,375
In fact if there was a lot of
vegetation floating on the water

226
00:09:54,399 --> 00:09:55,018
Uh-hm.

227
00:09:55,042 --> 00:09:57,257
that vegetation can have
fresh water on top of it.

228
00:09:57,281 --> 00:10:00,963
You know, a giant log mat maybe 100 miles
across with lots of branches and leaves,

229
00:10:00,987 --> 00:10:02,225
fresh water on top.

230
00:10:02,249 --> 00:10:03,941
But it can also,
as the fresh water soaks in

231
00:10:03,965 --> 00:10:06,687
you can get a freshwater
lens underneath it.

232
00:10:06,711 --> 00:10:07,326
Oh wow!

233
00:10:07,350 --> 00:10:10,330
So there’s tons of
places for fishes to hide

234
00:10:10,354 --> 00:10:13,539
but it might also be
—backing up a step—

235
00:10:13,563 --> 00:10:14,136
Uh-hm.

236
00:10:14,160 --> 00:10:17,072
that they could survive in both
fresh and salt water initially.

237
00:10:17,096 --> 00:10:18,705
And then they lose one ability.

238
00:10:18,729 --> 00:10:19,577
Yeah.

239
00:10:19,601 --> 00:10:21,297
So there’s tons of options here.

240
